FOREGROUND HERO — FIREWOOD BAG (REFERENCE-LOCKED; MATERIAL / COLOR / TRANSLUCENCY / SHAPE)

Material class: A semi-translucent, milky-white woven polypropylene sack for retail firewood — not agricultural orange/red/amber net, not open cargo-net holes, not kraft paper, not jute, not clear PVC, not solid opaque plastic sheet.

Weave / texture: Fine-to-medium tight cross-hatch weave (warp and weft visible as a regular grid), much denser than construction safety mesh — openings small; at normal viewing distance the body reads as continuous milky white fabric with subtle grid relief, not fishnet. Strands are narrow, slightly flattened extruded tapes with clear interlace crossovers. Surface finish: matte — low specular, no wet shine, no glossy plastic; at most very soft grazing light on weave ridges.

Plastic color (body): Clean milky white — like frosted milk glass — not yellowed, not cream, not beige, not grey bag. In shadow the white cools to grey-white; in strong rim light chalk white but still diffused, never glass-clear.

Opacity / translucency: The sack wall acts as a thin diffusing medium. Silhouettes, bulk, and orientation of logs inside are clear; broad color fields show through — dark bark masses vs pale split faces — forming high-contrast patterning through the fabric. Fine bark micro-detail is softened; edges are gentle, not razor-sharp as if no bag. No HD “window” transparency. Optional subtle real moiré only, not double-ghost.

Shape / interaction with contents: Rammed full of large split firewood. Fabric stretched taut over corners and curved faces → sharp tension creases, broad smooth bulges, irregular vertical undulations; side silhouette lumpy and organic, not a perfect cuboid.

Top — header and handle: Upper band is a more opaque white reinforced header (thicker strip): flatter, more solid white than the body, little to no fine wood detail bleeding through (faint bulk darkness only). Centered die-cut carrying handle: horizontal oval slot through the header — smooth inner cut edge, slightly bevelled, no cracks. Clean straight top edge; sharp horizontal transition from header down into woven body (subtle weld/stitch allowed).

Bottom / stance: Flat stable base, pack stands upright on patio or wood bed. Bottom corners subtly flare / bell outward under compressive weight (mild, not torn). Full footprint contact, not balanced on one point.

Contents visible through the milky weave — ORIENTATION LOCK (NON-NEGOTIABLE): Every piece inside the bag is a split billet whose LONG AXIS runs HORIZONTAL — parallel to the ground / parallel to the patio plane — like books laid flat in a vertical bookcase. NOT standing on end. NOT “pencils in a jar.” NOT toothpicks pointing skyward. The length of the wood does NOT run up the height of the bag.

How they fill the bag: Billets lie side-by-side and stacked in vertical layers inside the tall sack — each layer is horizontal, one horizontal row above the next, filling from bottom to the header. The height of the pack comes from many stacked horizontal layers, not from logs sticking upward.

What the camera sees through the front of the mesh: Because logs lie flat lengthwise, the primary read through the milky weave is END GRAIN and cleaved CROSS-SECTIONS facing the lens — soft ovals, circles, half-moons, wedge-shaped split faces, bark arcs at perimeters — dark bark vs pale split interiors as horizontal banding (row above row). Do not show long vertical runs of bark grain running floor-to-ceiling inside the bag (that implies length vertical — forbidden).

Roughly 5–6 large split pieces read as horizontal rows of cross-sections, packed tight, slight bulge between rows from weight. Bark: charcoal grey to deep earthy brown, rough ridged plates. Split faces / interiors: light tan to pale beige with visible grain — not neon yellow, not orange-stained wood as default.

Lighting on the bag: Specular only on weave high points, soft; fire glow may warm lower portion as ambient spill while plastic fibers stay white (warmth = light, not orange-dyed material).

