SPLIT FIREWOOD BED — NATURAL PILE (ENGINEERED HEAT MIX; MUST READ AS REAL BRAAI SPLITS)

What the bed IS: The ground under and around the bag is covered with many individual pieces of split hardwood — halves, quarters, and irregular wedges from axe / splitter / wedge fracture, not a tidy retail cube, not identical factory blocks, not a wall of perfect whole rounds standing on end like a fence.

Geometry of each piece (must be obvious in frame): Every chunk shows at least one prominent cleaved face — rough-to-medium smooth split plane with short, jagged, crystalline tear ridges (not long stringy pine/oak fibres). Bark shells on one or two sides; split face meets bark along ragged irregular junction with splinter tags, not a clean miter.

How pieces lie (natural disorder): Random 3D jumble — lengths staggered, angles varied (tilted, crossed, wedged under neighbours or under the bag). Real contact points, triangular voids between splits, not one flat perfect layer, not perfect parallel courses.

End grain vs split face: Radial checks from pith on visible end discs where applicable. Species diversity — no clone-identical chunks.

Species read in the split pile (several identities visible; align with doc):
• Geelhaak (Vachellia erioloba): canyon-furrowed grey–black bark; splits with dark purple-brown / oxblood heart + hard-edged yellow sapwood halo.
• Knoppiesdoring (Senegalia nigrescens): knobby bark; espresso / choc-chip heart; creamy-yellow sapwood; ragged interlocked splits.
• Sekelbos (Dichrostachys cinerea) — 1–2 thinner splits: mustard-ochre ring, reddish core on ends; slight oily satin on some planes; stubby spine stubs possible.
• Snuifpeul (Vachellia nilotica) — ≥1 wedge: lattice / braided bark; brick-red heart; pale sapwood.

Hard ban for the bed: Whole-round-only with no cleaved faces, neat hardware grid, clone-identical splits, birch bark, wet green wood, sanded furniture faces.

FIRE / COALS (LOW-MOISTURE HARDWOOD)

Flame: blue or transparent base blending to clean orange; steady, low flicker. No white steam, no thick grey smoke — thin bluish wisps at most. Coals blocky, holding structure, deep red to orange-white heat; fine pale ash in crevices — not instant powder.

